The smartphone-based fluorescence sensing platform mainly included image acquisition, signal detection, and quantitative analysis (shown in Fig. 7
                        A). The photos taken by the smartphone showed that the red-to-blue colorimetric probe was used to detect Cu2+ and L-Cys. The linear relationship between the ratio value of red to blue (R/B) and the concentration of Cu2+ range from 0.1 μM to 2 μM (showed in Fig. 7B). The equation was y = -0.319x + 2.549, R2 = 0.958 and the LOD was 95 nM. Also, as showed in Fig. 7C, there was a linear relationship between the concentration of 5–200 μM, the equation was y = -0.0515x + 2.005, R2 = 0.932. After adding L-Cys to the system, the fluorescence image gradually recovered from blue to red. There was a good linear relationship of y = 0.0147x + 1.688 (R2 = 0.987) between the ratio of red to blue (R/B) and L-Cys concentration from 0.06 μM to100 μM with a LOD of 50 nM (Fig. 6D). When the spiked recovery experiment was carried out with lake water as the actual samples, the recovery of red-to-blue colorimetric probe for Cu2+ and L-Cys was 98.2–101.6 % and 103.3–121.6 %, respectively (Table 2
                        ). All the above results showed that the smartphone-based fluorescence sensing platform was feasible to achieve on-site quantitative and rapid detection of Cu2+ and L-Cys.
